<h2>Where we started</h2>

<p>In 2024, I took on responsibility for the Funding Service, building on six years of digital investment that had established systems to manage data, calculate and publish allocations, issue contracts, and authorise payments. Operating at significant scale and complexity, the service delivered 58 formula-based grants worth £84bn across 202 funding lines in 2024–25, consistently reaching targets through experienced teams and well-established processes.</p>

<p>However, its incremental evolution has led to structural complexity, with funding delivered through a mix of systems, manual processes, and bespoke arrangements. Products had evolved beyond their original scope to manage edge cases, creating cross dependencies that made the service harder to scale or adapt. Change was often slow and costly, accountability was unclear, and siloed teams limited our ability to view and improve the service end to end.</p>

<p>These are not failures of individual systems or teams. They are symptoms of a service that has become fragmented, and where variance is absorbed rather than removed.</p>

<p>Over the first year, the focus was on creating the space to address this. We reshaped teams to move towards a more service-led, outcome-focused model, supported by better insight into user and service needs. In parallel, we redesigned our contract model, separating run and refine from improve and grow, reducing supplier reliance, improving accountability, and giving us greater control.</p>

<p>These changes reduced running costs and created a clearer separation between work on existing systems and improvement work. This allowed us to reinvest in discovery work to shape how the service evolves.</p>

<h2>Transformation projects</h2>

<h3>1) Communicating funding decisions</h3>

<p>Discovery work in year one highlighted consistent problems in how funding is communicated:</p>

<ul>
<li>providers use multiple systems to build a full picture of their funding</li>
<li>information is inconsistent in format and terminology</li>
<li>payment details vary by funding stream</li>
<li>statements are rebuilt each year, making the process costly</li>
</ul>

<p>Our aim for Alpha was to move from manual, bespoke processes to a scalable, data driven service that delivers clear and accurate information quickly.</p>

<p>The team designed reusable patterns for funding values, payment schedules, remittance information, and guidance, and tested them with users. In parallel, they assessed whether existing data could support automation.</p>

<p>Through proof of concept work and a small private beta, they built a microservice that generates statements automatically. Live data is now pulled via APIs rather than shared as static extracts, creating a more scalable service.</p>

<p>The first data driven statements went live in April, with rollout across all funding streams planned.</p>

<p>And just caught up with Lindy. She is buzzing that publishing allocations took seconds in SQL rather than piecing together five spreadsheets. [I am waiting on the calcs proposal, though still remain of the view that better for us to just publish the data columns and put the calculation in a word doc description]. </P.

