<h3>2) Operational data layer</h3>

<p>Another key finding from discovery was how disjointed data use was across the service. Operational data is spread across systems and teams, requiring it to be copied and reworked. This introduces errors, duplication, and reliance on manual extracts.</p>

<p>The operational data layer addresses this by creating a single, trusted source of funding data. Changes are made once, with clear audit trails, and flow across the service.</p>

<p>This shifts the model from a linear process to a hub and spoke approach, reducing duplication and dependencies.</p>

<!-- Image placeholder -->
<p><em>[Image: Linear data flow]</em></p>

<!-- Image placeholder -->
<p><em>[Image: Hub and spoke data model]</em></p>

<p>This reduces reliance on individual knowledge, improves auditability, and makes the service easier to scale and adapt.</p>

<p>Running a complex live service makes prioritisation difficult. Urgent issues are constant, but quick fixes often lead to workarounds that add complexity and variation.</p>

<p>Thinking about communications and data as service wide problems was made possible by introducing outcome focused teams that could work across system boundaries. This moved us away from reactive fixes and towards end to end solutions.</p>

<p> link to this - https://design-histories.education.gov.uk/improving-the-data-journey/reducing-complexity-through-a-single-trusted-source-of-funding-data</P>

<h2>Our North Star</h2>

<p>To build on this, we created a North Star for the Funding Service. It gives us a clear way to assess value, make trade offs, and focus on service wide outcomes.</p>

<p>It builds on four core pillars:</p>

<ul>
<li>sustain operational excellence</li>
<li>build service agility, efficiency, and resilience</li>
<li>increase certainty for providers</li>
<li>grow the number of grants delivered</li>
</ul>

<p>The North Star focuses on capabilities rather than systems. It describes a service where:</p>

<ul>
<li>funding enters through standard patterns</li>
<li>data collection is consistent</li>
<li>there is a single source of truth</li>
<li>variation is intentional</li>
<li>provider journeys are consistent</li>
<li>payments are controlled through a single exit point</li>
<li>communications are clear</li>
<li>rework is minimised</li>
</ul>

<p>These principles define what good looks like across the service. They help us decide not just what is urgent, but what is worth doing over time.</p>

<p>Through this work, it became clear that many smaller system changes were not delivering enough value to justify their cost. We also saw that shifting focus towards transformation would reduce activity that adds complexity.</p>

<p>From this, we made a deliberate decision to explore what a defined run state could look like.</p>

<h2>Run state</h2>

<p>A run state is a multi disciplinary team responsible for maintaining services that are no longer in active development.</p>

<p>To get there, we asked:</p>

<ul>
<li>what should this look like</li>
<li>how far away are we</li>
<li>what is getting in the way</li>
<li>what needs to change</li>
</ul>

<p>Current state: 73 people</p>

<p>We found three core issues:</p>

<h3>Working practices</h3>
<p>Too much manual work, repeated testing, and reliance on spreadsheets.</p>

<h3>Differences in funding design</h3>
<p>Unnecessary variation driven by legacy decisions.</p>

<h3>Technical architecture</h3>
<p>Inconsistent technology and environments limiting efficiency.</p>

<p>Together, these prevent consistent ways of working.</p>

<p>Target: 45 people in 12 to 18 months</p>

<p>A key part of this is a consistent technical foundation. We are building a central developer platform with standard hosting, deployment, monitoring, and security.</p>

<h2>2 to 3 year ambition</h2>

<p>Target: 26 people</p>

<p>We move to a capability based model focused on:</p>

<ul>
<li>data collection</li>
<li>calculation</li>
<li>contracting</li>
<li>payment</li>
<li>communication</li>
</ul>

<p>This depends on reducing unnecessary variation in policy design. From our work with policy implementation, we have identified areas of consistency such as funding year, data sources, and payment rhythms.</p>

<p>This gives us a foundation for reusable service patterns.</p>

<h2>Benefits of a run state</h2>

<p>The move to a run state brings a number of benefits:</p>

<ul>
<li>lower cost through smaller teams</li>
<li>better prioritisation</li>
<li>improved coordination</li>
<li>more flexible use of skills</li>
<li>more reliable services</li>
<li>easier scaling without duplication</li>
</ul>

<h2>What has been hard</h2>

<p>Getting buy in for foundational work has been challenging. Work like the data layer is critical but less visible.</p>

<p>The insight team also took time to settle, shifting from supporting delivery to shaping priorities.</p>

<p>Another challenge has been defining the true cost of running the service. Without a clear baseline, it is difficult to assess the impact of change.</p>

<p>Communication across a large team also remains an ongoing challenge.</p>

<h2>Summary</h2>

<p>Year 1 was about understanding the service and creating the conditions for change.</p>

<p>Year 2 has focused on turning that insight into action while continuing to run the live service.</p>

<p>Year 3 will focus on embedding these changes and moving to a lean run state.</p>

<p>Most importantly, we are moving away from short term fixes that fragment the service, and towards a model that allows us to scale and adapt without the cost of bespoke development.</p>
